---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import DarkHeader from '../../components/DarkHeader.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Is all PTFE the same for dry electrode processing? — Cooper Minehart"
  description="Battery-grade PTFE for dry electrode processing is a narrow material spec — molecular weight, emulsion polymerization, and particle size drive a ~200x price spread over bulk PTFE."
>
  <DarkHeader>
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6 pt-12 pb-10">
      <p class="section-label-light mb-3">Research &middot; Dry Electrode PTFE</p>
      <h1 class="font-serif text-4xl font-bold text-white mb-3">
        Is all PTFE the same for dry electrode processing?
      </h1>
      <p class="text-stone-300 max-w-2xl leading-relaxed">
        Oh no, it&rsquo;s more chemistry.
      </p>
    </div>
  </DarkHeader>

  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 pt-10 pb-24 text-[#1a1a1a]">

    <div class="prose-content space-y-5 text-[15px] leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        In the battery world, dry electrode manufacturing is one of the near-term
        innovations driving down cost and carbon intensity. Tesla is reportedly
        doing it for 4680 cells with NMC811. Incorporating PTFE and high-shear
        mixing processes give you a dry dough-like CAM mix that can be calendared
        in to a free standing film and then calendared on to your current
        collector (LiCAP, Maxwell, and AM Batteries have slight variations on
        this).
      </p>
      <p>
        PTFE (Teflon, Polytetrafluoroethylene) costs is fairly cheap as a battery
        input material (~$15 USD/kg, compared to ~$75 USD/kg for NMC811). I&rsquo;m an
        engineer (and not the chemical kind), do we need special PTFE for
        batteries?
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-serif text-xl font-semibold text-[#1a1a1a] pt-4">
        What do we want in our PTFE?
      </h2>
      <p>
        The PTFE fibrillates out under shear mixing (I imagine it like a web of
        mycelium). When calendared, this creates a free standing mixture. In
        order to polymerize, we care about three things
      </p>
      <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-3 text-[#333]">
        <li>
          <p><strong>Molecular weight</strong></p>
          <ol class="list-[lower-alpha] pl-6 mt-2 space-y-2">
            <li>
              Because PTFE is a polymer, you can make chains of different lengths
              (degree of polymerization, n, where n is the number of repeating
              CF<sub>2</sub> units). Higher polymerization &rarr; higher molecular
              weight &rarr; different mechanical structure. Schumme et. al shows
              that for PTFE used in dry electrodes, we need a molecular weight of
              about 10<sup>6</sup> g/mol (n ~10,000) to acheive the folded-ribbon
              structure that fibrillates well. Dispersity is a measure of the
              distribution of n (we want tight).
            </li>
          </ol>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong>PTFE Manufacturing method</strong></p>
          <ol class="list-[lower-alpha] pl-6 mt-2 space-y-2">
            <li>
              PTFE can be made through emulsion or suspension polymerization. I
              tried to understand the difference, but got in over my chemistry
              head quickly. The important aspect seems to be that for batteries
              we want PTFE manufactured by emulsion rather than suspension. This
              is adds a cost premium as most is suspension manufactured.
            </li>
          </ol>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong>Particle Size</strong></p>
          <ol class="list-[lower-alpha] pl-6 mt-2 space-y-2">
            <li>
              If you start with larger chunks of PTFE, you need to mix more,
              smaller you need to mix less. If you overmix, you break the
              tendrils and reduce integrity, undermixing you end up with
              heterogeneity.
            </li>
          </ol>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h2 class="font-serif text-xl font-semibold text-[#1a1a1a] pt-4">
        So&hellip; How much is this going to cost?
      </h2>
      <p>
        We have a cost floor, bulk PTFE (not battery grade) is $15 USD/kg. We
        have a cost ceiling, Min Kyung Kim quoted battery-grade PTFE at $2,805
        USD/kg in 2025. A 200x price uncertainty is not wonderful, and it&rsquo;s
        likely towards the floor (The Kim paper is likely quoting Sigma Aldrich,
        which is often ~100x cost of bulk orders).
      </p>
      <p>
        I&rsquo;m working on implementing a dry-cathode manufacturing model in BatPaC
        right now, we&rsquo;ll know soon how sensitive the cost savings of moving to
        NMP-free manufacturing are to PTFE prices.
      </p>

      <p class="pt-2">
        <a
          href="https://cooperminehart.substack.com/p/is-all-ptfe-the-same-for-dry-electrode"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener"
          class="text-forest-600 hover:underline font-medium"
        >
          Read the original on Substack &rarr;
        </a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
